```
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;

int fibonacci(int n) {
    if (n == 0) {
        return 0;
    } else if (n == 1) {
        return -1;
    } else {
        return fibonacci(n-1) + fibonacci(n-2) - fibonacci(n-3);
    }
}

int main() {
    int n;
    cout << "Enter the value of n: ";
    cin >> n;
    cout << "The " << n << "th number in the sequence is: " << fibonacci(n) << endl;
    return 0;
}
```

The `fibonacci` function takes an integer `n` as input and returns the `n`th number in the sequence. The base case is when `n` is 0, in which case the function returns 0. Otherwise, the function recursively calls itself with `n-1` and `n-2` as arguments and subtracts the result of calling `fibonacci(n-3)` from the sum of the two previous terms to get the `n`th number in the sequence.

In the `main` function, the user is prompted to enter the value of `n`, which is passed to the `fibonacci` function to get the corresponding number in the sequence. The result is then printed to the console.

